  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau suggests the fitness landscape under current world rules has been thoroughly explored. The issue is not algorithmic (mutator/selector) but structural: the organisms have exhausted the morphology + action + resource spaces available to them. Evolution needs new *dimensions to optimize*, not better *optimization of existing dimensions*. The three proposals each add orthogonal complexity axes: resource specialization (horizontal), temporal structure (temporal), and collective behavior (emergent higher-order). Pick the one that best matches where beauty actually lives in your simulation.; [medium] Introduce resource type differentiation: replace single 'energy' with 3 resource types (photosynthetic capacity, structural minerals, sensory bandwidth). Organisms must specialize cell types to harvest each resource. World generates spatially segregated resource gradients. — Current system likely has organisms at local optima for single-resource competition. Adding orthogonal resource dimensions creates unexplored fitness valleys—organisms must co-evolve different morphologies for different niches. Beauty emerges from resource specialization (color/texture = resource affinity). Survival ceiling breaks because multi-resource systems allow symbiosis and niche separation.; [medium] Add lifecycle stages with morphological transitions (larval → adult → reproductive form). Each stage has different movement rules, beauty evaluation, and survival constraints. Growth path is evolvable (when/how transitions trigger). — Plateau is likely because organisms have converged on a stable adult morphology. Developmental stages create temporal complexity—beauty can now include transition elegance, timing optimization. This breaks the symmetry assumption (same body throughout life). Efficiency gains from specialized stages (larva exploits different resources than adult). Reproduction timing becomes evolvable pressure.; [hard] Enable organism cooperation: allow cells to form long-range electrical/chemical connections within an organism, and permit multi-organism 'colonial' structures that inherit together. Fitness bonus for emergent group patterns (waves, flocking aesthetics). — Single-organism evolution has natural limits on complexity. Allowing collective structures creates fractal beauty possibilities and emergent behaviors (colonies exhibit patterns individual organisms cannot). Survival pressure shifts from individual-level to group-level coordination. Opens new beauty dimensions: synchronization, fractal geometry, wave propagation. Breaks the individual-organism assumption that likely constrains current morphology.",
